http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-09-30/features/9203280884_1_peter-hopkirk-russian-territory-great-game
	From the end of the Napoleonic era to the eve of World War I, Russia and England engaged in a protracted struggle among the mountains of Central Asia popularly known from some lines of Rudyard Kipling:

	``Now I shall go far and far into the North, playing the Great Game.``

	Kipling, the great poet champion of imperialism, borrowed the phrase from one of the game`s most ardent players, Captain Arthur Conolly, who was beheaded by the Emir of Bokhara in 1842 while trying to establish British control over that waystop on the ancient caravan route between China and the Near East.

	Like the Cold War, the Great Game was largely a proxy battle whose protagonists rarely confronted each other directly. Instead, English and Russian armies fought inumerable campaigns against the Muslim princes whose territories separated Russia from India, the crown jewel of the British Empire.

	``With the benefit of hindsight,`` notes Peter Hopkirk, author of the

	``Great Game,`` ``modern historians may question whether there was ever any real Russian threat to India, so immense were the obstacles that an invasion force would first have had to overcome.``

	But several generations of British statesmen and army officers thought the danger was real. Their Russian counterparts were plagued by morbid fears of British designs on Russian territory.

	``They will attempt to extend their influence to Kashgat, Persia, and all the Central Asian States bordering on us,`` a Russian newspaper warned its readers of England`s ambitions, ``and then will pose a direct threat to our interests in Asia.``

	Modivated by such suspicions, the game`s players progressively annexed most of the formerly independent powers of Central Asia.


were these motivations realistic?

