	...Yet neither side had trouble finding recruits. Russians and Englishmen donned native garb to undertake spying missions among Muslim peoples fiercely hostile to outsiders. During the Victorian Era, the naturally adventurous were morally reinforced by a conviction that they were doing God`s work by bringing European rule to the peoples of Asia.

	``Those were the days of supreme imperial confidence, unashamed patriotism and an unswerving belief in the superiority of Christian civilisation over all others,`` Hopkirk notes.


I guess recruited a lot of spies during great game. British spies said to be motivated by "doing God's work" in Asia


	The Great Game ended in a draw when Russia had to resign from the conflict after her defeat, in another imperial stuggle, by Japan in 1907. England and Russia agreeded to let neutral Afghanistan be a buffer zone between their Asian territories. Afterward, as Hopkirk notes, the Great Game was quickly entombed in ``unread memoirs, the occasional place name, and in the yellowing intelligence reports of that long-forgotten adventure.``


